I'm pretty astounded by the service (or lack thereof) from this place tonight. In a jovial mood for St. Patrick's Day, my friend and I stopped here for dinner and drinks. Upon arrival, we were surprised at how empty the place was, but we went to put in our order at the bar. The woman there who first greeted us and gave us menus was very nice.  Once we decided on what to get, a different gentleman, mid-length hair and white button-up, was there to receive our order. He already had a look of annoyance on his face, but I chalked it up to something else. My friend went to place our decided-upon order. Apparently one of the items was out, but the gentleman said he would check if they still had it, that they had a limited menu--understandable. My friend continued to place our order in and the gentleman was increasingly obstinate and aggressive; at one point, without checking on the menu item he said he would check on, simply said, "not going to happen."  Again, chalking it up to a bad day and a bad mood, we moved on with the order of food and drinks. He asked for our IDs; we obviously obliged. My friend, simply plopping his license on the wide bar counter, was accused for "throwing" it at him (which was not true at all). He continued to unrightfully admonish my friend as if he was being drunk and unruly (not at all; completely sober) and refused service. From my eyeline and earshot, the entire interaction seem as if he was itching to instigate some sort of verbal altercation and wanted to exercise some sort of (silly) power over a customer... it was laughable. Sorry, dude, if you don't like your job or your life, maybe do something about it? ¯_(ツ)_/¯  I don't know what was up with this guy. He evidently went into the interaction aggressively for whatever reason (it's 2019, take your toxic masculinity elsewhere), and we gladly left the place and proceeded to have a stellar experience at Kelly's Irish Times. Really glad we spent our time and money there instead.  I probably should've followed my friends' advice about this place, but seeing as it was down the block from my home, I thought I'd give it a chance in the spirit of the holiday... huge mistake. Makes sense why it was so empty on such an occasion. Seeing other similar reviews, I'm affirmed that it wasn't just us. Very disappointing experience, and definitely sullied my view of this place in my neighborhood (and I hate to write bad reviews about small businesses unless it's something really atrocious). Many other, more warm and accommodating places to visit than this one on this street.  EDIT: To reply to the reply, it was 100% this place, about 8:30/9:00 p.m. The live entertainment was over, and security was MIA. We were putting in our order to have in the beer garden. Rude gentleman was Caucasian with black, mid-length hair and hostility in his eyes, etc. etc. I live on H Street and know the area very well; 0% chance I've posted erroneously... kind of wish I did so I wouldn't have to write off a place in my 'hood. Oh, well.

Duffy's Irish pub served some of the best bar food I have had in DC.  Doesn't hurt that their pitchers aren't unbelievably expensive either (20).  But the real kicker here... AWESOME WINGS.  No really... AWESOME WINGS -- they have been voted best wings almost every year...  They come out crispy but juicy in the middle with a decent selection of flavors.  As an aside, I have had some awesome wings in town but the really good ones are usually gourmet -- and a plate of 4-6 will cost you somewhere in the neighborhood of 10-15 bucks ~2-3 dollars per wing.  I had 24 wings and paid ~1 dollar per wing.  Not so bad (but yes cheaper wings do exist)  I also highly recommend their tater-tots and their burgers..both were pretty delicious!
best dive bar in dc

Oh Duffy's!  Where would I be without you?   I tell you where.  Broke inside the 9:30 club paying full price for their expensive beer.  Pre-game Paradise!  Not only that, but Duffy's actually has pretty excellent food for a pub.  Fish and chips are nice and crisp and tasty.  Their wings are probably some of the best wings in DC and they aren't those freak steroid chickens either.  Want a sandwich?  They're HUGE and one is enough to feed two people.  The chicken club is really good.  I had that last time I was there.  I slept in the 9:30 club after eating that coma-inducing portion but oh so worth it.  The drinks are fairly priced for DC pricing standards.  Pitchers vary by price but they don't do those pansy little pitcher here.  You get a full, tall, sexy and curvy pitcher with your beverage of choice inside.  We've shared plenty of Yeungling pitchers here and I do believe they serve Smithwick's as well here, which is one of my favorite Irish Ale's.  Mmmmmm.  Bathrooms are nice and never look like a truck stop.  Ladies, I don't know about yours.  I worked at a pizza place in college and we literally fought to clean the men's  over the girl's.  What do you ladies do in there?!?!!  Also, if you like skeeball, it's not well known, but they have it hidden away!  Darts too, I believe.  I always love games at bars :)  Decent TVs everywhere to watch the game and there's a pay-for-play Internet Jukebox there as well.  Get your electric slide on while watching some AHL hockey...cuz the NHL can't do math and probably wont have a season this year.
